Abstract = {Originally published in Contemporary Psychology: APA Review of Books, 1997, Vol 42(7), 620-621. American Mixed Race: The Culture of Microdiversity (see record [rid]1995-97907-000[/rid]), edited by Naomi Zack, probes this problem of the color line from the perspective of racial diversity within individuals. The book argues that discussions of diversity (i.e., racial difference, multiculturalism) tend to focus on rigidly defined racial categories that impose group membership for individuals who differ from others in those groups and who may not belong to, or identify with, any particular group. The important contributions of American Mixed Race are twofold. First, the book is multidisciplinary. Contributors represent a number of specialties within the social sciences and humanities. The five sections of the book are autobiography, art, social science, public policy, and identity theory. Second, the book demonstrates the breadth of the microdiversity concept. Although racial distinctions will remain salient within the broader social culture well into the 21st century, the real challenge is recognizing and appreciating the commonalities within human experiences. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2012 APA, all rights reserved)},
