@article{2009-06130-01020090601,
Abstract = {Reviews the book, Race, ethnicity and nation: Perspectives from kinship and genetics by P. Wade (2007). Among the issues addressed in this volume are transnational adoption, ethnicity and assisted reproduction, mixed-race families, immigration, the transmission of ethnicity in post-Soviet Lithuania, and changing conceptions of Basque racial identity. This book is a useful and illuminating read for those with a particular interest in the ways in which new technologies and associated practices are changing ways of thinking about kinship in Europe. All the chapters in this volume ask questions about the supposedly ‘given’ nature of kinship. By interrogating the boundaries between nature and culture, the authors illustrate the varied ways in which the supposedly natural relations that are the basis of much racial and ethnic categorization are produced in local social, cultural, and historical worlds. However, despite its strengths, this volume has several weaknesses. A lack of explicitness in methodology may leave the reader wondering how some of the authors arrived at their conclusions. In addition, many of the studies rely heavily on media or print sources. The chapters that make use of both media sources and interviews or participant observation provide a stronger, more convincing and more varied body of evidence than those that rely more exclusively on media sources. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2012 APA, all rights reserved)},
