@article{2015-34712-00120150101,
Abstract = {Reviews the film, Black Or White directed by Mike Binder (2014). This film is about the life of Eloise, a mixed-race 7-year-old being raised solely by her White grandfather (Elliot Anderson) following the death of her maternal grandmother (his wife). When Elliot’s wife could look after Eloise, Rowena Jeffers, her paternal grandmother who is Black, had been content with the situation, but now, she says, her extended Black family is Eloise’s real family, and if the child grows up without them, she will have something fundamental missing from her sense of self. Part of our sociality is to think in terms of in-groups or out-groups, which can depend on things like nationality, gender, race, a sports team we support, and the kind of clothes we wear. With this kind of proclivity, something visible like color, although only skin deep, can be taken as significant. In the human history of international conflict, of socioeconomic status, and of slavery, color has become important because we have made it so. Black or White is a worthwhile film because it is not clear for any of us how much of our mental model of a person comes from assumptions and how much from our history of interaction with that person. How does an idea that “he’s a member of another race” or “she’s overdressed” stack up with “he did something I resent” or “she’s been really helpful”? We are affected not just by thoughts but by prethoughts. Is it our first thought, or prethought, that counts? This is the question the film puts forth. Best of all, it puts the question in a way that invites us to consider how we feel about such issues, and to think about the issues for ourselves. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2015 APA, all rights reserved)},
