@article{2006-01538-00320060101,
Abstract = {This letter to the editor discusses self-reported race and genetic admixture. The authors of this letter argue that the use of self-reported race in health research is debatable. They cite several other authors who have discussed the limitations in research analysis, inappropriate classifications of groups, and the use of suboptimal model for genetic cluster analysis. Despite advances in genetic analysis, clinicians and epidemiologists still disagree on the usefulness of race in clinical reporting. Sinha et al present data from an admixture analysis study they did on a sample population. The specifics of the study are explained. Although the need for cautious interpretation of racial data is indisputable, genetic analyses show that self-reported race is informative for the classification of genetic clusters. Although self-reported blacks in the United States are largely of mixed race, genetic admixture analyses show clear differences between self-reported blacks and whites, indicating that self-reported race provides a means for identifying distinct groups. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2012 APA, all rights reserved)},
