Abstract = {Reviews the book, A White Side of Black Britain: Interracial Intimacy and Racial Literacy by France W. Twine (2010). The book draws us into a thought-provoking journey that engages readers with the key participants and their immediate and extended families. The main purpose of the book was to present an ethnographic longitudinal analysis of how white members of mixed-race families in the Midlands of the United Kingdom deal with race, racism, whiteness and racial identity. This book explores the thinking and the discourses of white women who have established families with black Caribbean men. The book begins with the introduction of two new theoretical concepts: racial literacy and ethnic capital. It goes on to describe how the women in the longitudinal study cope with racism, how their thinking about race and whiteness has been challenged and changed over time, how their whiteness can be viewed either as a social liability or as a source of injury to their families and how they raise their ‘trans-racial’ children to become racially literate. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2012 APA, all rights reserved)},
