Abstract = {Examined, in 2 experiments, the effects of beneficiary–victim status and race on the reactions of 173 4th and 5th graders to an inequitable allocation. In Exp I, mixed-race dyads of Black or White Ss were subjected to profitable or unprofitable inequity by Black or White allocators. Ss were then allowed to request portions of a 2nd reward and were interviewed to assess inequity distress and their cognitive reactions to the experience of being a beneficiary or victim. Allocator's race was found to have a significant impact on the efforts of Black victims to redistribute rewards and to be relevant to all Ss' perceptions of the inequity. Ss' race and beneficiary–victim status influenced their interpretations of the initial allocation and the amount of distress experienced. Exp II examined the impact of race of observer and participant on observers' perceptions of an inequitable allocation. Overall results confirm the pervasive and complex impact of racial identity on reactions to inequity, pointing to its influence even on persons who have nothing tangible to gain or lose by their ratings and allocations. (20 ref) (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2013 APA, all rights reserved)},
