@inbook{2009-24368-00720100101,
Abstract = {As he took the stage with his family on election night, the crowd rose in unison in Grant Park in Chicago. Many will never forget that image of the first African American striding to the podium to deliver his presidential acceptance speech before 250,000 joyful and tearful souls. Barack Obama had just been elected the 44th president of the United States. Older members of the crowd uniformly expressed their disbelief: "I never thought I would ever see in my lifetime a black man elected to be president of the United States." Despite what appeared to be overwhelming odds when he announced his candidacy for president 21 months earlier, Barack Obama had ascended to the most powerful position in the world. Many of the elders in the crowd had witnessed the aftermath of the assassination of Martin Luther King on their grainy black and white television sets in 1968. They had seen news clips of Bull Connor and his police attack dogs in Birmingham, Governor George Wallace blocking the schoolhouse door to desegregation at the University of Alabama, Rosa Parks's refusal to be seated in the rear of the bus, the Watts Riots, and civil rights marches on Washington in the late 1960s. It's no wonder they couldn't conceive of Obama's ascent to power that night, a man who represented a culture and a race that had been oppressed since the origins of North American slavery in 1619. As biographers write of Obama's life, the term "resilience" will emerge as a predominant characteristic that helped carry him to a position of prominence on the world stage. Pundits will offer their opinions about how his sense of determination shaped his personality. They will reread and analyze Obama's books Dreams from My Father and The Audacity of Hope in order to gain insight into the part of his personality that provided him with a venue for overcoming all odds. Obama clarifies in his autobiographical works the many struggles and obstacles facing a young man of mixed race without a father. In