Abstract = {Children Who Wait is the report of a study that was commissioned by the Association of British Adoption Agencies following concerns about the number of children in local authority care waiting for permanent families. The study sought to understand the reasons why so many children in local authority care were waiting for permanent families. Their study was concerned only with children in long-term care under the age of 11 and living apart from their parents. At the time of the study there was a cultural adjustment to the diminishing numbers of babies available for adoption. The study indicates that a larger proportion of children in residential care had parents who objected to foster care. One of the factors which determined a decision for children to remain in foster or residential care was the difficulty in placing sibling groups, children from "black" or "mixed race" families, and the view that, through adoption, children should lose all contact with their biological families. The authors also described the effect of changes of social worker on children, saying that 80% of the children had a change of social worker within a two-year period. Social work needs to be more valued and have the resources needed to draw on existing knowledge to ensure that they are able to meet the needs of children who are waiting for them to act. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2012 APA, all rights reserved)},
