Abstract = {This chapter examines how prejudice is communicated in the media. The author focuses his discussion on representations of race and seeks an analytic frame that avoids recreating the system it attempts to critique. He seeks to articulate a lens for explicating media that neither embraces racialization and racial divisions nor accepts a priori racial definitions that maintain existing hierarchies. After reviewing the predominant trends in research on media representations of race (good-bad representations, discrimination, pedagogy about race, audience reception, images and stereotypes, and uses and gratifications), he describes recent trends that examine Whiteness, diaspora, exhilic experiences, and "otherness." From these trends, he builds his discussion based on the assumption that media representations are sites of political contestation involving disparities of power. He is concerned about how media images participate in the construction of political realities in addition to reflecting social practice. He uses a text, Doubles, which problematizes binary, essentializing racial purity by focusing on bi- and mixed-race people to challenge images of racial purity and unpack the practice of substituting "American" for "White." (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2012 APA, all rights reserved). (introduction)},
