@article{1985-12781-00119830601,
Abstract = {Describes the activities, experiences, and concerns of members of 7 support groups that helped participants work on issues related to different- or mixed-race living during a 3-yr period. 25 White, 12 Black, and 1 Chinese Ss lived with partners and/or children of a different or mixed race. Initial group encounters were intellectual and somewhat educational as Ss shared their life experiences. Armoring was used by Black and other Ss of color to promote self-caring during direct encounters with racist experiences. Co-leaders of the group were a Black clinician (the author) paired with a graduate student who had or was experiencing a mixed race relationship. Most Ss moved to the host environment of the spouse upon marriage. Group activity focused on establishing a definite identity for children and reinforcing it with models to support pridefulness. Group concerns about childrearing practices were racial: White Ss were criticized for being too permissive with children, and Black Ss were criticized by spouses for being too strict and by their families for being too permissive. Ss needed support and clarification around the question of what is developmental and what is cultural. Ss were trained to take leadership roles and continued meeting in their homes. A 5-item bibliography is appended. (1 ref) (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2012 APA, all rights reserved)},
