Abstract = {Originally published in Contemporary Psychology: APA Review of Books, 1996, Vol 41(1), 19-20. Is there a "color line" in psychotherapy? Certainly there are stereotypes developed and preserved by psychological theorists and therapists that serve as expressions of established expectations and assumptions. These have, it is argued in this book (see record [rid]1994-98466-000[/rid]), prevented adequate treatment and service delivery to women who do not fit their image of a model client. The color line, a term drawn from recent U.S. history, was an actual demarcation drawn down hallways and waiting rooms to keep "colored people" (as Blacks and others were designated) separate from Whites as part of enforced segregation. This compendium of conceptual analyses, case examples, and suggestions for therapy invites those who would address the therapeutic needs of women to consider change. The goal of this book, which is well conceived and carefully organized, is to alert therapists to the changing realities of the U.S. demographics and prepare them to deliver services to an increasingly diverse population. This book makes a respectable effort at covering the topics of importance for women of the major ethnic groups now in the United States. As it stands, they include chapters on at least six ethnic groups (African Americans, American Indians, Asians, Latinas, women from the Caribbean, and women from India) and five special populations (professionals, lesbians, women of mixed race, refugees, and women who are battered). If there is any major omission, it is the surprising lack of any detailed discussion of the therapist-client relationship. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2012 APA, all rights reserved)},
